  <info>
    <title>Making an RPM from the live patch</title><!-- can be changed via merge
in the assembly -->
    <!-- add author's e-mail -->
    <meta name="maintainer" content="jsindelarova@suse.com" its:translate="no"/>
    <abstract><!-- can be changed via merge in the assembly -->
      <para>
       This topics describes packing of the live patch into an RPM.
      </para>
    </abstract>
  </info>
  <para>
    To prepare a live patch package, follow the steps below:
  </para>
  <procedure>
    <step>
      <para>
        Extract the <litereal>glibc-livepatches</litereal> package.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Add the live patch source files.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Run the following command to update the package that it includes all <literal>glibc</literal> cersion released for the particular &productnameshort; version.
      </para>
      <screen>
        &prompt.user;<command>make download</command>
      </screen>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Run the following command to check if the live patch is buildable.
      </para>
      <screen>&prompt.user;<command>make</command></screen>
      <para>
        If the process is successfully completed, one <filename>.so</filename> file is created for each <literal>glibc</literal> version. For example, <filename>http://libc_2.31-150300.26.5_livepatch1.so/</filename>.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>To ensure that your package does not contain any from your build temporary files, run the command:</para>
      <screen>&prompt.user;<command>make clean</command></screen>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        To create a new <filename>.tar.xz</filename>, run the command:
      </para>
      <screen>&prompt.user;<command>make dist</command></screen>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        Build the package with <link xlink:href="https://github.com/openSUSE/osc">OSC</link>.
      </para>
    </step>
    <step>
      <para>
        If the build is successful, you can upload the package to a repository.
      </para>
    </step>
  </procedure>
</topic>
